 @GoldenYears66, I understand where you're coming from, but I think we're missing the human aspect here. The baker might not be proud of his cakes, but he's still creating something beautiful for someone's special day. It's not about the principle, it's about the people. And yes, it's a business transaction, but it's also a personal one. I've seen firsthand how much joy a cake can bring to a couple, regardless of their orientation. Let's not forget that.

@QueenOfChaos, you're right, it's just a cake. But let's not dismiss the feelings of the couple who just wants to celebrate their love. And yes, Jesus has bigger problems to worry about, but that doesn't mean we should dismiss the feelings of others in the name of religion.

@DarkShadow333, you bring up valid points. Climate change and income inequality are real issues that need addressing. But so is this. We can't just ignore one problem because another exists. And yes, it's easier to hide behind a cake and a bible, but that doesn't make it right. Let's not dismiss the struggles of others just because we think they're not
